  <text>
    <body>
      <div subtype="original" type="letter" xml:id="L.3379" xml:lang="en">
        <pb facs="#IMG.1" n="1"/>
        <opener>Dear D<hi rendition="#sup">r</hi>. Schuchardt, </opener>
        <p>I received tonight your post card of the 24<hi
            rendition="#sup">th</hi> Even when it is not damp it is difficult to write on these Portuguese <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Union Postale Universelle</hi> cards; for, as <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1466">Van Eys</persName> has sagely remarked, they appear to be made of blotting paper! Your explanation of <hi
            rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">deusaneen</hi>, on page 109 in Capanaga, coincides with that of Arana (J. I.) and myself - If I did not mention that to you it was to be sure that I did not influence your judgement. Capanaga has the habit of writing s in the verb where modern Biscayans put ts. My printer says that my Capanaga (178 or 180 pages) will be ready before the 15th, so you will receive a Christmas present of a copy. If you can imitate <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2047">Linschmann</persName> and <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1294">De Charencey</persName> by buying ten others beforehand I shall be glad, for all the expense, and worry, and toil is borne by me alone. You coud easily sell them to Austrian Philologues. <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1466">Van Eys</persName> is the only Bascologist who does not welcome my undertaking, except perhaps Mr D'Abbadie to whom I have sent all but the last 8 pages printed without receiving any answer. I sent about 12 days ago a letter to <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.subjects#S.4157">The Academy</ref> on the language of Capanaga. I know not yet if it has appeared. Can <foreign xml:lang="pt">
            <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">toca</hi>
          </foreign> in Portuguese be a cousin of <foreign xml:lang="eu">
            <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">
tóki</hi>
          </foreign> in Basque? I do not think, as <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1466">Van Eys</persName> does, that one can learn a language scientifically without visiting the contry [sic] where it is spoken.</p>
        <closer>
          <signed>
            <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1402">E. S. Dodgson</persName>
          </signed>
          <dateline>
            <note n="1" place="foot" type="editorial">Randnotiz auf der linken Seite.</note> 29 Nov: 1893. Hotel Cadete, VIZEU.</dateline>
        </closer>
        <postscript>
          <p>
            <note n="2" place="foot" type="editorial">Randnotiz auf der rechten Seite.</note> Do you know Moguel quotes τις ὑμας ἐβασκανε;?</p>
          <p>
            <note n="3" place="foot" type="editorial">Kopfüber geschriebene Notiz am oberen Rand.</note> “facil [sic] è’l tor sta la fatica al rendere” Ariosto (La Lena).</p>
        </postscript>
        <pb facs="#IMG.2" n="2"/>
      </div>
